* Zucker=E2=80=99s game: Jeff Zucker=E2=80=99s RedBird IMI recently succeed=
ed in offloading The Spectator to hedge fund chief Paul Marshall for an eye=
-popping =C2=A3100 million, and will accept final bids for The Telegraph in=
 just two weeks. As you=E2=80=99ll recall, due to foreign ownership restric=
tions, the U.K. government forced Zucker to sell both the magazine and the =
paper shortly after he=E2=80=99d acquired them.

It=E2=80=99s unclear what The Telegraph will fetch: I=E2=80=99m told that s=
ubscription and revenue growth has slowed at the Tory broadsheet since Zuck=
er first bought the asset. Meanwhile, the auction has been going on so long=
 that the initial euphoria may have faded. Oh/and:
The anti-Zucker legislation that capped foreign sovereign ownership at 5 pe=
rcent has limited the available pool of prospective buyers.

So, who=E2=80=99s still in the mix? Three potential buyers: Marshall and Ke=
n Griffin certainly have the money, and might like to pair The Telegraph wi=
th The Spectator. Former Mirror C.E.O. David Montgomery is also said to be =
