On Thursday, just before his appearance at a Goldman Sachs investor confere=
nce, David Zaslav announced that Warner Bros. Discovery had struck a new di=
stribution agreement with Charter that will increase the overall fees the d=
istributor pays to air CNN, TNT, and WBD=E2=80=99s other TV networks. The d=
eal, which Zaz closed ahead of schedule, gave him a lot to crow about at th=
e conference and, more importantly, sent his beleaguered stock soaring 10 p=
ercent=E2=80=94its best one-day performance in nearly a year.

Of course, the deal was significant because it came on the heels of WBD for=
feiting its NBA rights after a mismanaged negotiation and absorbing a stagg=
ering $9.1 billion write-down on the value of its cable networks. Skeptical=
 analysts have correctly warned that Zaz could get screwed in the rights re=
newal negotiations without the
NBA=E2=80=94in fact, according to the work of my partner John Ourand, Comca=
st was motivated to overpay for league rights partly to do just that. And, =
to be sure, the fees for a neutered TNT, itself, remained flat at roughly $=
3 per sub in the Charter deal. But Zaz was nevertheless able to tout a =E2=
=80=9Cterrific deal=E2=80=9D overall. Meanwhile, The Wall Street Journal cl=
aimed the deal would =E2=80=9Clay the foundation=E2=80=9D for WBD=E2=80=99s=
 negotiations with other providers, and specifically Comcast.

That=E2=80=99s great press, but the Charter deal has almost no bearing on Z=
az=E2=80=99s future negotiations with Comcast, as well-placed Comcast sourc=
es confirmed to me this week. Reports on the Charter deal omit a key releva=
nt detail: WBD board member and Zaz sensei John Malone=E2=80=99s Liberty Me=
dia also owns a significant, 26 percent stake in Charter. Malone isn=E2=80=
=99t putting his finger on the scale, obviously, but he=E2=80=99s effective=
ly setting the market for himself.
=E2=80=9CLiberty wasn=E2=80=99t going to undermine WBD through Charter=E2=
=80=9D any more than Brian Roberts would let Comcast hose NBCUniversal, one=
 veteran media executive noted. Meanwhile, this source added, =E2=80=9CComc=
ast is not going to care one iota about a Charter deal with WBD.=E2=80=9D

Indeed, as another source told me back in early August, Roberts and Comcast=
 are likely to =E2=80=9Cput the screws=E2=80=9D to WBD during their next ri=
ghts negotiations. In retrospect, Roberts=E2=80=99 aggressive play for Zaz=
=E2=80=99s NBA rights seems to have been part of a brilliant and multifacet=
ed corporate chess maneuver: By submitting a bid that Zaz and his debt-sadd=
led company couldn=E2=80=99t match, Roberts won coveted sports rights for N=
BC and deprived his competitor of the asset that commands hefty subscriber =
fees. And no, March Madness, MLB, NASCAR, and a smattering of other assets =
aren=E2=80=99t going to fill that void (still, congrats to Zaz for getting =
the French Open, another excuse to return to the Crillon). As
one Comcast source told me this week, the Charter deal =E2=80=9Cdoesn=E2=80=
=99t lay a foundation. It doesn=E2=80=99t mean anything.=E2=80=9D

On a related note, some industry insiders believe that Roberts might also l=
everage CNN=E2=80=99s low ratings to keep fees down during the negotiations=
=2E That might seem like a moderate=20=
act of war, but it=E2=80=99s not entirely=
 unfounded. Outside of a few major political events, including its presiden=
tial debate and Kamala Harris interview, CNN has been putting up some of th=
e worst ratings in its history. During Tuesday=E2=80=99s debate, CNN drew j=
ust over 4 million viewers, coming in sixth place behind all the other majo=
r broadcast and cable news networks, even though the network ostensibly tra=
nsported its entire stable of primetime broadcasters and anchors down to Ph=
iladelphia. Notably, it marked the first time in the history of presidentia=
l debates that MSNBC outperformed CNN in total viewers.

The Zaz Bundle Love Language

On the streaming front, Zaz said that Max was poised to add 6 million subsc=
ribers and touted its forthcoming tie-up with Disney+ and Hulu. Of course, =
the Hulu piece is also complicated by Comcast, which remains in a stalemate=
 with Disney over relinquishing its one-third ownership position in that jo=
int venture. (My partner Bill Cohan will have some more insight into Zaz=E2=
=80=99s streaming promise to Wall Street in Dry Powder on Sunday. Sign up h=
ere ( https://puck.news/newsletters/dry-powder/?utm_campaign=3DIn+The+Room+=
