          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">On Thursday, just b=
efore his appearance at a Goldman Sachs investor conference, <b>David Zasla=
v </b>announced that Warner Bros. Discovery had struck a new distribution a=
greement with Charter that will <i>increase</i> the overall fees the distri=
butor pays to air CNN, TNT, and WBD=E2=80=99s other TV networks. The deal, =
which Zaz closed ahead of schedule, gave him a lot to crow about at the con=
ference and, more importantly, sent his beleaguered stock soaring 10 percen=
t=E2=80=94its best one-day performance in nearly a year. <br/><br/>Of cours=
e, the deal was significant because it came on the heels of WBD forfeiting =
its NBA rights after a mismanaged negotiation and absorbing a staggering $9=
=2E1 billion write-down on the value of=
 its cable networks. Skeptical analyst=
s have correctly warned that Zaz could get screwed in the rights renewal ne=
gotiations without the
NBA=E2=80=94in fact, according to the work of my partner <b>John Ourand</b>=
, Comcast was motivated to overpay for league rights partly to do <i>just t=
hat</i>. And, to be sure, the fees for a neutered TNT, itself, remained fla=
t at roughly $3 per sub in the Charter deal. But Zaz was nevertheless able =
to tout a =E2=80=9Cterrific deal=E2=80=9D overall. Meanwhile, <i>The Wall S=
treet Journal </i>claimed the deal would =E2=80=9Clay the foundation=E2=80=
=9D for WBD=E2=80=99s negotiations with other providers, and specifically C=
omcast.<br/><br/>That=E2=80=99s great press, but the Charter deal has almos=
t <i>no</i> bearing on Zaz=E2=80=99s future negotiations with Comcast, as w=
ell-placed Comcast sources confirmed to me this week. Reports on the Charte=
r deal omit a key relevant detail: WBD board member and Zaz sensei <b>John =
Malone</b>=E2=80=99s Liberty Media also owns a significant, 26 percent stak=
e in Charter. Malone isn=E2=80=99t putting his finger <i>on the scale</i>, =
obviously, but he=E2=80=99s effectively setting the market for himself.
=E2=80=9CLiberty wasn=E2=80=99t going to undermine WBD through Charter=E2=
=80=9D any more than <b>Brian Roberts </b>would let Comcast hose NBCUnivers=
al, one veteran media executive noted. Meanwhile, this source added, =E2=80=
=9CComcast is not going to care one iota about a Charter deal with WBD.=E2=
=80=9D<br/><br/>Indeed, as another source told me back in early August, Rob=
erts and Comcast are likely to =E2=80=9Cput the screws=E2=80=9D to WBD duri=
ng their next rights negotiations. In retrospect, Roberts=E2=80=99 aggressi=
ve play for Zaz=E2=80=99s NBA rights seems to have been part of a brilliant=
 and multifaceted corporate chess maneuver: By submitting a bid that Zaz an=
d his debt-saddled company couldn=E2=80=99t match, Roberts won coveted spor=
ts rights for NBC <i>and </i>deprived his competitor of the asset that comm=
ands hefty subscriber fees. And no, March Madness, MLB, NASCAR, and a smatt=
ering of other assets aren=E2=80=99t going to fill that void (still, congra=
ts to Zaz for getting the French Open, another excuse to return to the Cril=
lon). As
one Comcast source told me this week, the Charter deal =E2=80=9Cdoesn=E2=80=
=99t lay a foundation. It doesn=E2=80=99t mean <i>anything</i>.=E2=80=9D<br=
/><br/>On a related note, some industry insiders believe that Roberts might=
 <i>also</i> leverage CNN=E2=80=99s low ratings to keep fees down during th=
e negotiations. That might seem like a moderate act of war, but it=E2=80=99=
s not entirely unfounded. Outside of a few major political events, includin=
g its presidential debate and <b>Kamala Harris </b>interview, CNN has been =
putting up some of the worst ratings in its history. During Tuesday=E2=80=
=99s debate, CNN drew just over 4 million viewers, coming in sixth place be=
hind all the other major broadcast and cable news networks, even though the=
 network ostensibly transported its <i>entire</i> stable of primetime broad=
casters and anchors down to Philadelphia. Notably, it marked the first time=
 in the history of presidential debates that MSNBC outperformed CNN in tota=
l viewers.<br/></td>
